<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06035096 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06035096 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SAN-FRANCISCO; ...; AUTO; ROAD; TRAFFIC; PARK; VIOLATION; CRIME; BEGIN;EQUIPMENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  In a city where there are 234,000 more automobiles than legal parking spots,the Department of Parking and Traffic soon will begin giving chronic parkingoffenders The Boot.;    The Denver Boot, that is.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  California News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  CLAMPING DOWN IN S.F.CHRONIC PARKING OFFENDERS DESTINED FOR THEBOOT  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Starting today, a scofflaw with more than 10 unpaid parking citations inthe city may find a yellow, clamp-like device affixed to his or her vehicle'sfront wheel to keep it from moving.;    The owner of the immobilized vehiclemust then pay the outstanding parking fines at Municipal Court, plus a $50de-booting fee, said Rina Cutler, executive director of the Department ofParking and Traffic.;    &quot;We've got 50 boots now,&quot; she said Thursday, &quot;andwill have another 50 next week.&quot; The boot is used in several citiesnationwide, including Chicago, Boston and Denver, where it originated in thelate 1950s.;    The device is just one more way parking officials hope toalleviate San Francisco's legendary parking problems. They have hired extrameter maids, installed 2,700 additional parking meters, and continued towingtens of thousands of cars.;    Still, parking spaces are rare, and illegallyparked and abandoned cars abound. &quot;This is just one more tool,&quot; Cutler said.;   She said the boot has been controversial wherever it is introduced, but thatshe expects most San Francisco residents to applaud it.;    &quot;I've found thatin neighborhood meetings, on radio talk shows, the majority of the public issupportive,&quot; she said. &quot;It doesn't affect the majority who do pay their fineson time.&quot;;    However, she does expect lawsuits.;    &quot;I'm certain that bymid-next week, someone will file a legal challenge,&quot; said Cutler. But, sheadded, in every city where similar lawsuits have been filed and wound up atthe state Supreme Court level, the boot's legality has prevailed.;    Angrypeople also will try and remove the boot from their wheels, she predicted.;   Drivers who do manage to remove the boot without getting caught still won'tescape justice, Cutler said.;    &quot;I'll have their license plate number, nameand address,&quot; she said. &quot;I will always be able to find your vehicle again.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  McClatchy News Service  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  San Francisco  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910204  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  343  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday February 4, 199100035096,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>